x4freetext: Positron annihilation in flight.
Energy resolution (FWHM) ranged from about 200 keV at
the lowest energy (E(gamma) = 10 MeV) to around 400
keV at the highest energy (E(gamma) = 33 MeV).
Neutron 4pi detector, consisting of a 61-cm cube
of paraffin containing 48 BF3 tubes arranged in four
concentric rings of 12 tubes each.
Direct photoneutron detection.
Ring-ratio neutron multiplicity measurement.
A noteworthy feature of this experiment is the use of
a remotely controlled pneumatic 8-position revolving
sample changer, which allowed all of the samples, as
well as a blank sample and a neutron calibration
source, to be inserted into the center of 4pi neutron
detector sequentially without changing the beam tuning
or any other experimental conditions.  This feature
enabled relative cross section measurements to be made
with a precision of about 2%.  This is much better
than the overall absolute accuracy of about 5% typical
of recent measurements near the peak of the giant
resonance of medium and heavy nuclei.
Photoneutrons from each sample and from a sample-blank
were measured, both with and without the annihilation
target present.  After the recorded neutron events
were corrected for pileup in the detector, the neutron
backgrounds (annihilation target removed) were
substracted for both the positron and electron
measurements.
Because the energy spectrum of the annihilation-plus-
Bremsstrahlung radiation differs from that of purely
Bremsstrahlung photons, a measured correction was
applied to the ion-chamber (beam monitor) response to
normalize the electron data to the positron data.
The normalized electron data then were substracted from
the positron data, leaving the neutron counts which
result only from the annihilation radiation.
The measured sample-blank data, normalized to equal
photon flux, were substracted from the target data to
give the net target results.
After a small correction for the neutron multiplicity
in each ring, the data were corrected for the energy-
dependent efficiency of the neutron detector using the
ring-ratio result for each energy.
The data were then converted to the photoneutron cross
sections by applying the measured ion-chamber response
per photon, the known number of target nuclei in the
beam, and a small correction for the photon
attenuation in the sample.
A multiplicity analysis of the number of neutrons
recordered in each beam burst allows the (gamma,n) and
(gamma,2n) yields to be extracted simultaneously and
independently.
Statistical errors only.
Uncertainty in absolute cross section does
not exceed 10%, and results mainly from normalization
uncertainty and from the uncertainty in the absolute
photon flux (about 5%).
These results resolve outstanding discrepancies among
previous measurements.
In view of the continuing controversy concerning
discrepancies between the absolute values of certain
photoneutron cross sections measured at Livermore and
Saclay, the photoneutron cross sections near the peak
of the giant dipole resonance for Zr, I, and Pb, were
remeasured where previous results from the two
laboratories were quite different, and for Pr and Au,
where the previous results were essentially the same.
The new results are in agreement with both sets of
previous data for Pr and Au, with the Livermore
results for Zr, and with Saclay results for Pb;
for I, they fall midway between the two previous data
sets.
Converted from Berman compilation.
